<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-"></h2>


<div id="" class="width-full maxw-full bg-carbon-05 padding-bottom-9 padding-top-9 hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-featured-link">
	<div class="grid-container grid-container-block padding-x-0 padding-top-9 desktop:padding-top-0">
		<div class="grid-row flex-align-center">
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 padding-x-3 desktop:padding-right-5 margin-bottom-5">
				<div class="label margin-bottom-2">About</div>
				<h2 class="page-heading-md">The Webb Mission</h2>
				<p class="p-md">Webb is the premier observatory of the next decade, serving thousands of astronomers worldwide. It studies every phase in the history of our Universe, ranging from the first luminous glows after the Big Bang, to the formation of solar systems capable of supporting life on planets like Earth, to the evolution of our own Solar System.</p>
									<a href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/webb/about-overview/" target="_self" class="button-primary button-primary-md link-external-false" aria-label="">
						<span class="line-height-alt-1">Learn More</span>
						<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><circle class="button-primary-circle" cx="16" cy="16" r="16"></circle><path d="M8 16.956h12.604l-3.844 4.106 1.252 1.338L24 16l-5.988-6.4-1.252 1.338 3.844 4.106H8v1.912z" class="color-spacesuit-white"></path></svg>
					</a>
					
			</div>
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 desktop:padding-left-5">
				<div class="width-full">
					<div class="hds-media-wrapper margin-left-auto margin-right-auto"><figure class="hds-media-inner hds-cover-wrapper hds-media-ratio-cover"><img width="1024" height="683" src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?w=1024" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="A Engineer looks over one of the James Webb Space Telescope&#039;s primary mirror segments." style="transform: scale(1); transform-origin: 50% 50%; object-position: 50% 50%; object-fit: cover;" block_context="nasa-block" loading="lazy" decoding="async" srcset="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp 2048w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=300,200 300w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=768,512 768w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=1024,683 1024w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=1536,1025 1536w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=400,267 400w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=600,400 600w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=900,600 900w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=1200,800 1200w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-4808870003-8558a2628a-k-jpg.webp?resize=2000,1334 2000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure><figcaption class="hds-caption padding-y-2"><div class="hds-caption-text p-sm margin-0">This is a photo of one of the James Webb Space Telescope's primary mirror segments coated with gold by Quantum Coating Incorporated. It's NOT a flight segment, it's the engineering design unit. The photo was taken at BATC by Drew Noel.</div><div class="hds-credits">Photo by Drew Noel</div></figcaption></div>				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-"></h2>


<div id="" class="width-full maxw-full bg-carbon-05 padding-bottom-9 padding-top-9 hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-featured-link">
	<div class="grid-container grid-container-block padding-x-0 padding-top-9 desktop:padding-top-0">
		<div class="grid-row flex-align-center">
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 padding-x-3 desktop:padding-right-5 margin-bottom-5">
				<div class="label margin-bottom-2">About</div>
				<h2 class="page-heading-md">Webb&#039;s Science Goals</h2>
				<p class="p-md">The James Webb Space Telescope is a giant leap forward in our quest to understand the Universe and our origins. Webb is examining every phase of cosmic history: from the first luminous glows after the Big Bang to the formation of galaxies, stars, and planets to the evolution of our own solar system. Learn about the 4 main science themes for Webb.</p>
									<a href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/webb/science-overview/" target="_self" class="button-primary button-primary-md link-external-false" aria-label="">
						<span class="line-height-alt-1">Learn More</span>
						<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><circle class="button-primary-circle" cx="16" cy="16" r="16"></circle><path d="M8 16.956h12.604l-3.844 4.106 1.252 1.338L24 16l-5.988-6.4-1.252 1.338 3.844 4.106H8v1.912z" class="color-spacesuit-white"></path></svg>
					</a>
					
			</div>
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 desktop:padding-left-5">
				<div class="width-full">
					<div class="hds-media-wrapper margin-left-auto margin-right-auto"><figure class="hds-media-inner hds-cover-wrapper hds-media-ratio-cover"><img width="1024" height="954" src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?w=1024" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="This image is from Webb’s NIRCam instrument, which saw this nebula in the near-infrared." style="transform: scale(1); transform-origin: 50% 50%; object-position: 50% 50%; object-fit: cover;" block_context="nasa-block" loading="lazy" decoding="async" srcset="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp 4833w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=300,279 300w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=768,715 768w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=1024,954 1024w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=1536,1430 1536w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=2048,1907 2048w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=400,373 400w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=600,559 600w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=900,838 900w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=1200,1118 1200w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/webb-flickr-52212049510-bb98d2eab6-5k-jpg.webp?resize=2000,1863 2000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure><figcaption class="hds-caption padding-y-2"><div class="hds-caption-text p-sm margin-0">NASA’s Webb Captures Dying Star’s Final ‘Performance’ in Fine Detail</div><div class="hds-credits">NASA, ESA, CSA, and STScI</div></figcaption></div>				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-"></h2>


<div id="" class="width-full maxw-full bg-carbon-05 padding-bottom-9 padding-top-9 hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-featured-link">
	<div class="grid-container grid-container-block padding-x-0 padding-top-9 desktop:padding-top-0">
		<div class="grid-row flex-align-center">
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 padding-x-3 desktop:padding-right-5 margin-bottom-5">
				<div class="label margin-bottom-2">About</div>
				<h2 class="page-heading-md">The Spacecraft</h2>
				<p class="p-md">The Webb Space Telescope is the largest, most powerful and most complex telescope ever launched into space . It&#039;s design and development history stretches back before the Hubble Space Telescope was launched.  Learn about the design, the major components and subsystems of Webb and see Webb in 3d in a 3d Solar System.</p>
									<a href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/webb/spacecraftoverview/" target="_self" class="button-primary button-primary-md link-external-false" aria-label="">
						<span class="line-height-alt-1">Learn More</span>
						<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><circle class="button-primary-circle" cx="16" cy="16" r="16"></circle><path d="M8 16.956h12.604l-3.844 4.106 1.252 1.338L24 16l-5.988-6.4-1.252 1.338 3.844 4.106H8v1.912z" class="color-spacesuit-white"></path></svg>
					</a>
					
			</div>
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 desktop:padding-left-5">
				<div class="width-full">
					<div class="hds-media-wrapper margin-left-auto margin-right-auto"><figure class="hds-media-inner hds-cover-wrapper hds-media-ratio-cover"><img width="1024" height="768" src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?w=1024" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="Webb Spacecraft Rendering" style="transform: scale(1); transform-origin: 55% 47%; object-position: 55% 47%; object-fit: cover;" block_context="nasa-block" loading="lazy" decoding="async" srcset="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png 2564w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=300,225 300w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=768,576 768w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=1024,768 1024w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=1536,1151 1536w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=2048,1535 2048w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=400,300 400w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=600,450 600w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=900,675 900w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=1200,900 1200w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Webb_1.png?resize=2000,1499 2000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure></div>				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-"></h2>


<div id="" class="width-full maxw-full bg-carbon-05 padding-bottom-9 padding-top-9 hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-featured-link">
	<div class="grid-container grid-container-block padding-x-0 padding-top-9 desktop:padding-top-0">
		<div class="grid-row flex-align-center">
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 padding-x-3 desktop:padding-right-5 margin-bottom-5">
				<div class="label margin-bottom-2">About</div>
				<h2 class="page-heading-md">The International Webb Team</h2>
				<p class="p-md">Webb is for the world, and from the world. Thousands of skilled scientists, engineers and technicians from 14 countries (and more than  29 U.S. states, and Washington, D.C.) contributed to the design, build, test, integration, launch, commissioning and operations of Webb. It is a joint NASA/ESA/CSA mission. Assembly and testing of the mirror and instruments occurred at NASA Goddard (GSFC).</p>
									<a href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/webb/webb-team/" target="_self" class="button-primary button-primary-md link-external-false" aria-label="">
						<span class="line-height-alt-1">Learn More</span>
						<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><circle class="button-primary-circle" cx="16" cy="16" r="16"></circle><path d="M8 16.956h12.604l-3.844 4.106 1.252 1.338L24 16l-5.988-6.4-1.252 1.338 3.844 4.106H8v1.912z" class="color-spacesuit-white"></path></svg>
					</a>
					
			</div>
			<div class="grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-6 desktop:padding-left-5">
				<div class="width-full">
					<div class="hds-media-wrapper margin-left-auto margin-right-auto"><figure class="hds-media-inner hds-cover-wrapper hds-media-ratio-cover"><img width="1024" height="576" src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?w=1024" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="A full disk view of the earth from GOES 16, GOES East on the vernal Equinox." style="transform: scale(1); transform-origin: 48% 47%; object-position: 48% 47%; object-fit: cover;" block_context="nasa-block" loading="lazy" decoding="async" srcset="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg 1920w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=300,169 300w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=768,432 768w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=1024,576 1024w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=1536,864 1536w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=400,225 400w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=600,338 600w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=900,506 900w, https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/goes16-vernalequinox-flickr50209599563-99acbeb180-b.jpg?resize=1200,675 1200w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure><figcaption class="hds-caption padding-y-2"><div class="hds-caption-text p-sm margin-0">A full disk view of the earth from GOES 16, GOES East on the vernal Equinox.
</div><div class="hds-credits">NOAA / NASA</div></figcaption></div>				</div>
